<section class="block-section do">
  <span class="section-tag">Do</span>
  <h2>Today's work — choose one path</h2>
  <p class="sub">Pick how you want to rehearse. The first 15 min is submission; rehearsal runs the middle 50; whole-class share is the last 15.</p>
  <div class="choice-intro">
    <strong>Learning Intention:</strong> I can rehearse a defense of my dossier and articulate the strongest objection a panelist might raise — with at least one move from the Defending Your Work taxonomy.
  </div>
  <div class="choice-board">
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">A</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Paired defense rehearsal (3-min Q&A each)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">Pair up. Partner A defends 3 min while Partner B asks 2-3 panelist questions. Switch. Use the observation guide for specific feedback. Default for most students.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Pairs · Default</span>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">B</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Solo rehearsal with partner-as-audience</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">If you want to rehearse the 5-min talk uninterrupted first, do that — partner listens silently and gives feedback after. Then swap. Good if your nerves benefit from a quiet first run.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Pairs · Choice</span>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">C</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Self-review using the rubric</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">For students whose defense is in an alt format (video, written response): self-review your draft against the <a href="/foundations/the-rubric/">rubric</a>. Mark which strand each section serves. Submit with the dossier.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Solo · Choice</span>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">D</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Anticipating-questions worksheet</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">If oral rehearsal is high-anxiety, work the anticipating-questions worksheet instead — list 5 questions a panelist would likely ask and draft your answer to each. Bring this to tomorrow's defense.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Solo · Practice</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

